This paper deals with reasoning about programming language calculi involving named bound variables, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories of computer science. The most likely sub-category is cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) because the paper presents an extension of Nominal Isabelle that includes new definitions of alpha-equivalence and establishes the reasoning infrastructure for alpha-equated terms, which involves logical reasoning. The second most likely sub-category is cs.PL (Programming Languages) because the paper deals with programming language calculi and general bindings, which are ubiquitous in programming language research. The third most likely sub-category is cs.SE (Software Engineering) because the paper presents an infrastructure for reasoning about programming language calculi, which is relevant to software engineering. The fourth most likely sub-category is cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) because the paper deals with formal reasoning about programming language calculi involving named bound variables. The fifth most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language) because the paper deals with reasoning about programming language calculi involving named bound variables, which is relevant to natural language processing.
